# METHODOLOGY BLOCK
"SALES CALL SOP
"Lead the Frame. Shift the Belief. Sell the Change."
A complete internal guide to executing high-converting sales calls based on first principles, not gimmicks.

🎯 OBJECTIVE:
Don’t convince. Don’t educate. Don’t chase.
Control the frame. Build emotional contrast. Remove uncertainty.
Your goal isn’t to “close”—your goal is to lead them to clarity so they close themselves.

🧩 STRUCTURE: 6 PHASES (with full depth)

1. THE FRAME TAKEOVER
"If you lose the frame, you lose the sale."
⏱️ Duration: 2–3 mins
What it is:
* The prospect walks in thinking they’re in charge.
* You flip the frame by calmly taking control, not through force — but by setting the rules of the game.
Key Lines:
“Hey, appreciate you jumping on. Here’s how I like to run these calls so we don’t waste time…”
“I’ll ask some questions to see if we’re even a fit. If it makes sense, I’ll walk you through how we help people like you.”
Why it works:
* People trust leaders with a plan.
* Setting expectations relieves social pressure — and keeps the prospect focused.
* This shifts their brain into evaluation mode, not negotiation mode.
Bonus: Use “this might not be a fit” language early to build authority and safety.

2. THE PROBLEM DEEP DIVE
"The better you diagnose, the less you have to sell."
⏱️ Duration: 10–15 mins
What it is:
* You ask layered, open questions that force them to confront the problem in their own words.
* Don’t surface-level this — go deep. Dig until they say something that sounds like pain, shame, or fear.
Killer Questions:
* “What’s not working right now?”
* “How long has that been going on?”
* “What have you tried to fix it?”
* “Why do you think it hasn’t worked?”
* “What happens if this stays the same for 6 more months?”
* “What’s that costing you, directly or indirectly?”
Techniques:
* Mirror + silence: Just repeat their last few words and pause. They’ll fill the gap.
* The ‘stack’: Stack 3 questions before they respond to trigger introspection.
* Empathize but don’t rescue: Let them sit in their pain.
Why it works:
* When they say the problem out loud, they own it.
* Pain said = pain felt = higher intent.
* You’re not pitching — you’re extracting fuel for later.

3. THE BELIEF FLIP
"You’re solving the right problem… with the wrong tools."
⏱️ Duration: 3–5 mins
What it is:
* You reveal why their current model will never get them what they want.
* This is not a pitch. This is a reframe.
* You’re breaking their attachment to the old game.
Example:
“You’re doing everything right… inside a broken machine.”
“Most people think they need more leads — but what they really need is predictability.”
How to do it:
* Use contrast: “You’ve been chasing referrals. They work… until they don’t.”
* Normalize the failure: “Everyone tries [X] first. That’s not wrong — it’s just not scalable.”
* Don’t blame the person — blame the strategy/system.
Why it works:
* People are emotionally attached to how they work.
* You can’t sell a new vehicle until you total the old one.
* This moment builds anticipation: “So what does work?”

4. THE NEW VEHICLE INTRO
"Not a better hammer — a different tool entirely."
⏱️ Duration: 3–5 mins
What it is:
* You finally introduce your method/system/process, but without going deep into the offer yet.
* Think philosophy before product.
Key Language:
“Here’s how we solve that: We install a system that… [brief mechanism].”
“It’s not about more [X] — it’s about making [Y] automatic.”
How to position:
* Describe your unique mechanism in 1–2 sentences.
* Anchor it to what they just told you:
“Remember when you said [insert pain]? This fixes that.”

Proof tactically:
* “We just helped [ideal avatar] do [result] in [timeframe].”
* Use only identity-matching proof — people want to see themselves in the win.
Why it works:
* This is where you flip them from skeptic to believer.
* People need a vehicle they can believe in before they’ll drive it.

5. THE CLARITY CLOSE
"No pressure. Just a fork in the road."
⏱️ Duration: 5–10 mins
What it is:
* You explain what it looks like to work together
* You ask them to decide based on clarity, not persuasion
Key Lines:
“Want me to show you what it would look like if we helped you implement this?”
“Here’s what the next 30 days would look like…”
“If you’d rather keep doing what you’re doing, totally fair — but this is what the new path looks like.”
What to include:
* High-level process
* Support they’ll get
* How the transformation happens
* What their new normal looks like
* Timeframe + logistics
Conversion Technique:
* Use status visioning:
“Imagine 90 days from now… you’re not guessing anymore. You’re scaling by choice.”

* No “closing tactics.” Just clarity.

6. THE OBJECTION NEUTRALIZER
"Every objection is really a hidden belief that hasn’t shifted yet."
⏱️ Duration: As needed
When objections happen:
* You missed a belief shift.
* You skipped emotional contrast.
* You rushed the logic.
What to do:
* Go back to pain: “Help me understand — is the current problem not painful enough?”
* Separate the surface from the source: “Is this about the money, or uncertainty it’ll work?”
* Future pace again: “Let’s imagine you fix this without us. What would that look like?”
Hormozi’s big idea:
Don’t react. Re-diagnose.


📌 FINAL REMINDER 
“If they don’t believe the old way is broken, they won’t buy the new way. And if they don’t believe you understand them, they won’t believe your system will work for them.”



🎭 THE PURPOSE OF SALES: CREATE EMOTIONAL CONTRAST
"People don’t buy because of what they’ll get. They buy because of what they’ll avoid."

🧠 CORE INSIGHT
“You’re not transferring information — you’re transferring emotion.”
Our central thesis is that most people get sales completely wrong. They focus on logic: features, benefits, frameworks, guarantees.
But buyers don’t move because of logic — they move because of contrast. Specifically:
The emotional pain of staying stuck must become greater than the fear of making a change.
Your job in sales is not to educate — it’s to widen the emotional gap between:
STAYING STUCK	MOVING FORWARD
Confusion	Clarity
Insecurity	Control
Wasted time	Predictability
Status quo	Elevated status
Delay	Momentum
🎢 CONTRAST CREATES TENSION — AND TENSION CONVERTS
We describes sales as an emotional roller coaster.
And tension is the fuel that powers it.
If the prospect doesn’t feel:
* The pain of their current path
* The upside of the new path
* And the gap between them...
Then no price, feature, or pitch will move them.
This is why he says:
“A mediocre offer, sold with contrast, will beat a great offer, pitched flat.”

🔄 YOU’RE NOT A CLOSER — YOU’RE A CONTRAST BUILDER
We reframes the rep’s role entirely. You’re not “convincing.” You’re leading someone to a mirror and asking them:
“Are you okay with this version of your life?”
Contrast is created by:
* Extracting vivid pain (see: Problem Deep Dive)
* Painting an identity-driven future (see: Status visioning)
* Forcing choice through non-coercive clarity
“If nothing changes, is that okay with you?”
“6 months from now, what changes if you don’t do this?”

You want the prospect thinking:
“Shit. I can’t keep doing this.”

💥 THE MOMENT THAT SELLS: WHEN THEY BREAK
We explains that every high-close sales call has a moment — not where you pitch, but where they break.
They say something like:
* “I’ve been spinning my wheels for 2 years.”
* “I’m tired of watching others pass me by.”
* “I know I’m capable of more — I just don’t know how to get out of this.”
That’s the conversion moment.
Your offer just becomes the logical solution to the emotional decision they’ve already made.

🔥 HOW TO INTENTIONALLY BUILD EMOTIONAL CONTRAST
Here’s how we structures emotional contrast into the conversation — regardless of the offer:

1. Stretch the Pain
“How long has this been happening?”
“What have you tried so far?”
“How much is this costing you?”
“What does it feel like when that happens?”
You’re not asking for facts.
You’re asking for feelings.

2. Reveal the Hidden Cost
Most people underestimate what their problem is actually costing them.
You need to stretch their perspective:
“What’s the cost of continuing this for another 6 months?”
“How many opportunities are you losing because of this?”
“What else is being impacted — time, health, relationships?”
This is where regret begins to build.

3. Destroy the Status Quo (Softly)
Never insult. Never shame. Just make the status quo obviously broken.
“I hear this all the time — smart operators stuck doing $30K/month with $200K/month problems.”
“If hustle was the answer, you’d be rich already.”
Let them feel the absurdity of their current system.

4. Future-Pace the Win
Once they’re emotionally out of their current world, show them the new one.
“Imagine waking up knowing what your pipeline looks like for the next 60 days.”
“Imagine clients come to you — you don’t pitch anymore, you filter.”
It’s not about “the product.” It’s about the new identity they step into.

5. Create the Fork in the Road
Finally, you draw the line. You show the contrast between two choices:
🟥 Keep going → same pain, uncertainty, waste
🟩 Say yes → clarity, progress, leadership
“Totally up to you — but the next 6 months are going to pass either way. The only question is: what’s different on the other side?”
You don’t push. You don’t beg.
You just hold the mirror.

🛑 WHAT NOT TO DO
* ❌ Don’t jump into pitch mode too early
* ❌ Don’t list benefits like it’s a brochure
* ❌ Don’t “educate” instead of emotionally connect
* ❌ Don’t relieve their pain too early (they’ll lose urgency)
* ❌ Don’t assume logic will drive the decision


🔺 THE BELIEF TRIANGLE: SHIFT THESE OR LOSE THE SALE
"All objections are just unshifted beliefs."

🧠 CORE INSIGHT
“You don’t need to be better at overcoming objections — you need to be better at pre-empting belief gaps.”
We explains that every sale hinges on just three core beliefs being aligned.
If even one of these beliefs is missing, the deal dies.
Not because they don’t want the result — but because their mental model of how to get there hasn’t been restructured.
He calls this framework the Belief Triangle:

🔺 The 3 Core Beliefs That Must Be Shifted
Belief	What it Means	What Happens if Missing
① “This will work for me”	They see themselves succeeding with it	“Sounds good… for someone else”
② “It will work now”	They believe timing is right and results can come fast	“Maybe later…”
③ “You’re the right person to help me”	They trust you’re credible, safe, and proven	“I’ll think about it / shop around”
🎯 1. BELIEF #1: “This will work for me”
🔍 Category: Relevance
This is the biggest silent killer of sales.
People rarely say it out loud — but if they don’t see themselves in the solution, they ghost you.
Why it breaks:
* You used vague, generic proof (“we help businesses”)
* You didn’t show enough identity-matching examples
* You never repeated their words back to them
* You explained the product — not their outcome
How we fixes it:
“Every proof point must look like a mirror.”
“Don’t show me a case study — show me my future.”
🛠 Fix it by:
* Referencing people with their same role, size, problem
* Repeating their exact phrases when describing the outcome
* Using anchored language:
“You mentioned your biggest headache is X… this directly fixes that.”

Example Line:
“We helped a 3-person agency just like yours go from 20K/mo with no pipeline to 50K/mo and fully booked in 6 weeks — without spending a dollar on ads.”

🎯 2. BELIEF #2: “It will work now”
🔍 Category: Urgency + Timing
This belief handles the mental stall:
“I like it… but I’ll wait.”
Which Hormozi sees as death.
Why it breaks:
* You didn’t create cost of inaction
* You made the result feel long, abstract, or delayed
* You didn’t anchor a quick win or “momentum point”
* The offer sounded complicated or heavy
How we fixes it:
“People don’t need to believe they’ll be rich in 12 months — they need to believe they’ll feel momentum in 7 days.”
🛠 Fix it by:
* Emphasizing speed to signal:
“In 72 hours, you’ll have a new sales system live.”

* Showing what happens if they wait:
“Every week you delay, 5 more high-ticket buyers go somewhere else.”

* Giving a low-friction first milestone:
“Your first client using this system usually lands within 10–14 days.”

Example Line:
“This isn’t a 6-month wait-and-see thing. You’ll know by next week if it’s working — because you’ll already have leads showing up.”

🎯 3. BELIEF #3: “You’re the right person to help me”
🔍 Category: Trust + Authority
Even if they believe in the solution, and that it works now — they won’t buy if they don’t trust you.
This is especially critical in high-ticket services.
Why it breaks:
* You sound like a salesman, not a peer
* You over-explained or over-pitched
* Your energy is needy or uncertain
* You never established authority or social proof
How Hormozi fixes it:
“The person with more certainty wins the call.”
“They don’t need a savior — they need a guide who’s been where they are.”
🛠 Fix it by:
* Showing calm confidence, not hype
* Name-dropping relevant wins or clients subtly
* Saying “we might not be a fit” early to create authority
* Speaking like a doctor, not a hype man:
“Here’s what I’d recommend based on what you said.”

Example Line:
“We’ve helped 100+ firms in exactly your situation — under 10 employees, stuck on referrals, tired of inconsistent growth. This system came from solving that pattern over and over.”

📌 BONUS: How to Use the Triangle in Real Time
We watches reps fumble calls by missing which belief isn’t there.
They treat all “no’s” the same.
Instead, he suggests:
